								<p class="lead">In this section you will learn how to set up, or create, a new folder on the C: Drive.<p>
								<p>As an empowered user, you will learn to control the storage and organization of your data into folders and files on your computer. This way you can decide if you want to store your data in the default location or another folder that you create.</p>


<p>To create the folder, the process is the same for all versions of Windows. 

<ol>
									<li>Go to the location where you want to create a new folder and right click in a blank area.</li>
									<li>From the popup menu, select New.</li>
									<li>From the next popup menu, select Folder. You must then type the name of the folder and hit Enter.</li>
																								</ol>
		
								<img class="space" src="images/filesandfolders/folder.jpg"/>
								<hr>					




<p>The process for creating a folder is easy. Now you must decide where you want to create the folder. Your computer may be used and shared by more than one person, especially if you use a computer at a school, library, workplace or even in your home. When a computer is shared by more than one user, each user has an individual <strong>log in</strong>. A log in (also called user name, log in name, log in ID, log on) is a name and a password that belong to an individual computer user and allow that person access to and use of the machine.</p>
								<p>With more than one person using the computer, you need to make sure you know exactly where your folders and files are located on either the C: drive or hard drive or another storage device, like a USB or jump drive.</p>
								<p>As you learned in Computer Basics, the default location for storing data for most Microsoft programs is on the C: Drive in a folder called My Documents (Classic Windows and Windows 7) or Documents (Windows Vista). You have the option to store your documents in the default location or you can create a place of your own. First you will be shown the default location and then you can decide if you want to use it.</p>
								<p>Let’s begin by opening up your C: drive. With your C: drive open on the screen, you will need follow the instructions for creating a folder that match the version of Windows you have on your computer.</p>
							
